ACT IV. SCENE IV.

Phaedria, having gone home to look for the Eunuch, finds him; and as he had no suspicion of the project that had been formed between Chaerea and Parmeno, drags him out, fully assured that he is the same Pythias meant, and preparing for further ssight by the change of his dress. But when Pythias saw him, and knew nothing of him, he is perfectly astonished. Upon questioning a little, he comes to know all the truth‚ and is strangely disconcerted; but willing, if possible, to bring himself off, he makes Dorus deny every thing he had said.
